+   Free blocks are organized into 12 doubly-linked explicit free lists,
+   one per size class. The size class boundaries are:
+     Class 0:  <= 32  bytes  (minimum block size only)
+     Class 1:  <= 64  bytes
+     Class 2:  <= 128 bytes
+     Class 3:  <= 256 bytes
+     Class 4:  <= 512 bytes
+     Class 5:  <= 1024 bytes
+     Class 6:  <= 2048 bytes
+     Class 7:  <= 4096 bytes
+     Class 8:  <= 8192 bytes
+     Class 9:  <= 16384 bytes
+     Class 10: <= 32768 bytes
+     Class 11: >  32768 bytes
+
+   The 12 list-head pointers are stored at the very beginning of the
+   heap (before the prologue block), avoiding any global array variable.
+
+2. BLOCK STRUCTURE
+   Every block (free or allocated) carries an 8-byte header and an
+   8-byte footer that each encode the block's total size and allocation
+   status. The minimum block size is 32 bytes (header + two free-list
+   pointers + footer). Free blocks store a prev-pointer at bp+0 and a
+   next-pointer at bp+8 in the otherwise-unused payload area.
+
+3. 8-BYTE ALIGNMENT
+   Block sizes are rounded up to multiples of 8 (WSIZE) rather than
+   the original 16, reducing internal fragmentation for odd-sized
+   requests.
+
+4. ALLOCATION POLICY
+   mm_malloc searches for a first fit starting from the smallest size
+   class that can contain a block of the requested size, then advances
+   to larger classes if needed. This combines the speed of first-fit
+   with the reduced fragmentation benefit of segregated storage.
+
+5. FREE-LIST MANAGEMENT
+   Blocks are inserted at the head of their size class list (LIFO order)
+   for O(1) insertion. Removal is also O(1) via the doubly-linked
+   structure.
+
+6. COALESCING
+   Freed blocks are immediately coalesced with adjacent free neighbors
+   using the standard four-case boundary-tag algorithm. Adjacent free
+   blocks are removed from their respective size-class lists before
+   merging, and the merged block is re-inserted into the correct list.
+
+7. OPTIMIZED REALLOC
+   mm_realloc avoids unnecessary malloc/copy/free cycles in two cases:
+   (a) The current block is already large enough -- return ptr unchanged.
+   (b) The immediately following block is free and the combined size
+       suffices -- absorb it in-place without copying.
+   (c) The current block is at the end of the heap (next block is the
